Cross et al., (2001) confirm this by presenting six features which differentiate effective and ineffective knowledge sharing relations: 
“1)knowing what other person knows and thus when to turn to them; 
2) being able to gain timely access to that person; 
3) willingness of the person sought out to engage in the problem solving rather than dump information; 
4) a degree of safety in the relationship that promoted learning and creativity; 
5) the factors put by 







Geert Hofstede






; and 
6) individual characteristics, such as openness"  (pp 5). This fits in nicely with Granovetter’s argument that “Weak ties provide people with access to information and resources beyond those available in their own social circle; but strong ties have greater motivation to be of assistance and are typically more easily available.” (Granovetter, 1983, pp 209)
